                <head>90. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On January 11, at a news conference, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName> was asked several questions concerning the Baghdad Pact.
                    He mentioned U.S. sympathy toward its formation and his own personal interest.
                    He then said, “On the question of its further development, the United States has
                    no particular views. We have not urged any other countries to join the
                    pact.”</p>
                <p>Regarding U.S. membership, the Secretary said, “I think we would consider joining
                    the Baghdad Pact if and when it seemed in doing so it would be a contribution to
                    the general stability of the area. We do not consider it as an isolated
                    act.”</p>
                <p>For the complete transcript of the news conference, see <hi rend="italic"
                        >American Foreign Policy: Current Documents, 1956</hi>, page 561.</p>
            </div>
